properties.name: Community Information
properties.webBody:
This Community Information is being issued for Goormalibee.
  • This Community Information message replaces the Community Information message issued at 8:56pm Sunday 21 December.
  • The large grassfire that has been burning in Goormalibee, between Tarnook Road and the Broken River, is under control.
  • Small fires may still be burning in this area, and firefighters are patrolling the fire with heavy plant and machinery to completely extinguish it.
  • Beware of dangerous tree hazards.
  • Smoke may still be visible from nearby communities and roads.
  • Only local traffic can travel in this area.
There are road closures at the:
  • intersection of Goomalibee Road and Tarnook Road
  • intersection of Tarnook Road and Burness Road
  • intersection of Terret Rd and Goomalibee Road.
There is no immediate threat to the community and no action is required.
This message was issued by Country Fire Authority.

Unless the situation changes, this will be the last message issued for this fire

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au.
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226.
  • VicEmergency app.
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfires).
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
Accessibility:
The following service can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Services on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service for assistance and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.name: Advice
properties.location: Wodonga, Springhurst, Chiltern, Barnawartha, Bonegilla, Kiewa and surrounds
properties.webBody:
This Advice is being issued for Wodonga, Springhurst, Chiltern, Barnawartha, Bonegilla, Kiewa and surrounds. 
  • North East Water has advised that as of today, Tuesday 23 December, the tap water in Wodonga, Bandiana, Baranduda, Barnawartha, Bonegilla, Chiltern, Ebden, Kiewa, Killara, Leneva, Springhurst, Tangambalanga and Logic Centre is not safe to drink without boiling first.
  • Rainwater has potentially contaminated a treated water storage tank in Wodonga.
  • The rainwater is believed to have entered the tank during Sunday’s heavy rainfall event.
  • Consumption of unboiled water may lead to diarrhoea, cramps, headaches or other gastro like symptoms.
If you live or work within Wodonga, Bandiana, Baranduda, Barnawartha, Bonegilla, Chiltern, Ebden, Kiewa, Killara, Leneva, Springhurst, Tangambalanga and Logic Centre, you must boil tap water before drinking.
What you should do:  
  • Boil water before drinking it, or drink bottled water.
  • Boil water for food preparation, cleaning fruit and vegetables, making ice and for preparing baby formula.
  • Boil water for brushing teeth.
  • If you have special needs, call North East Water on 1300 361 644 or go to www.newater.com.au
To ensure water is safe, you should: 
  • Heat water until a continuous and rapid stream of air-bubbles is produced from the bottom of a pan or kettle (kettles with automatic shut-off switches are suitable). 
  • Allow water to cool before use. 
  • Store water in a clean, closed container for later use. 
  • Be careful when boiling water to prevent scalding or burns.
  • If you are concerned that you may have been affected by contaminated water, contact your doctor or Nurse-on-Call.
It is safe to use unboiled water for:
  • Washing your hands.
  • Showering and bathing.
  • Flushing toilets.
  • Washing dishes (ensure dry before use).
  • Clothes and garden watering.
Ensure water is not ingested whilst bathing.
Impacts in your area: 
  • North East Water is conducting testing in the area.
  • Results are expected within 24 hours.
  • These results will inform the next steps.
This message was issued by Department of Health.

The next update is expected by 24/12/2025 07:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226 
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter
  • ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
Accessibility:
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency. 
  • To access this information in other languages, call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline. 
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact the National Relay Service and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

This Community Information is being issued for Natte Yallock, Rathscar West .
  • There is a haystack fire at Avoca-Bealiba Road, Rathscar West. 
  • Haystack fires are not likely to spread into grassland but do generate a lot of smoke. 
  • Smoke may be visible from nearby roads and communities as firefighters pull apart the hay to extinguish the fire. 
There is no immediate threat to the community and no action is required.
This message was issued by Country Fire Authority.

Unless the situation changes, this will be the last message issued for this fire.

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 

  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au.
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226.
  • VicEmergency app.
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfires).
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
Accessibility:

  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service for assistance and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.
